<paragraph id="F91126771073FFD4A8617D62998E1A99" blockId="27.[806,1422,1142,1591]" box="[806,996,1142,1163]" pageId="27" pageNumber="99">
<emphasis id="CBDAFA651073FFD4A8617D62998E1A99" box="[806,996,1142,1163]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="99">Taxonomic notes</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F91126771073FFD4A8617D80999C1825" blockId="27.[806,1422,1142,1591]" pageId="27" pageNumber="99">
Small species (
<quantity id="3E568B921073FFD4A8B37D809E211ABB" box="[1012,1099,1172,1193]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.1" pageId="27" pageNumber="99" unit="mm" value="9.1">9.1 mm</quantity>
, 
<typeStatus id="261598D51073FFD4AF2D7D809EA61AB8" box="[1130,1228,1172,1194]" pageId="27" pageNumber="99">holotype</typeStatus>
) with slender abdomen; although males of 
<taxonomicName id="3EAE5DF41073FFD4AFD47DA79F581AD5" authority="Ricarte &amp; Marcos-García &amp; Hancock &amp; Rotheray, 2012" authorityName="Ricarte &amp; Marcos-García &amp; Hancock &amp; Rotheray" authorityYear="2012" box="[1171,1330,1202,1224]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Quichuana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longicauda" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="CBDAFA651073FFD4AFD47DA79F581AD5" box="[1171,1330,1202,1224]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="99">Q. longicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="D0E9471E1073FFD4AE7E7DA79FE41ADA" box="[1337,1422,1203,1224]" pageId="27" pageNumber="99" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be readily separated from males of 
<taxonomicName id="3EAE5DF41073FFD4AFAF7DC599271B17" baseAuthorityName="Macquart" baseAuthorityYear="1855" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Quichuana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angustiventris">
<emphasis id="CBDAFA651073FFD4AFAF7DC599271B17" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="99">Q. angustiventris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the absence of a thick mat of yellow hairs obscuring the background colour of the frontal triangle, genitalia are similar in both species; genitalia of 
<taxonomicName id="3EAE5DF41073FFD4A8167C5899851B72" authority="Ricarte &amp; Marcos-García &amp; Hancock &amp; Rotheray, 2012" authorityName="Ricarte &amp; Marcos-García &amp; Hancock &amp; Rotheray" authorityYear="2012" box="[849,1007,1355,1377]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Quichuana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longicauda" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="CBDAFA651073FFD4A8167C5899851B72" box="[849,1007,1355,1377]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="99">Q. longicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="D0E9471E1073FFD4A8B17C589E211B73" box="[1014,1099,1356,1377]" pageId="27" pageNumber="99" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
differ from genitalia of 
<taxonomicName id="3EAE5DF41073FFD4A8617C7E99801B6D" baseAuthorityName="Macquart" baseAuthorityYear="1855" box="[806,1002,1386,1407]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Quichuana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angustiventris">
<emphasis id="CBDAFA651073FFD4A8617C7E99801B6D" box="[806,1002,1386,1407]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="99">Q. angustiventris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having superior lobes shorter and more developed on the anterior surface (
<figureCitation id="61953AF21073FFD4AE5E7C9C9F301B8D" box="[1305,1370,1416,1439]" captionStart="Figures 5–8" captionStartId="3.[144,234,1358,1377]" captionTargetBox="[370,1195,806,1326]" captionTargetId="figure-206@3.[367,1199,802,1328]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figures 5–8. Quichuana male genitalia. 5–7, Quichuana angustiventris: 5, hypandrium, lateral view; 6, epandrium, lateral view; 7, left half of epandrium, anterior view. 8, Quichuana longicauda sp. nov., apical part of hypandrium, lateral view. Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5408539" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5408539/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="99">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
); in both males and females of 
<taxonomicName id="3EAE5DF41073FFD4AF237CB39F691BAE" authority="Ricarte &amp; Marcos-García &amp; Hancock &amp; Rotheray, 2012" authorityName="Ricarte &amp; Marcos-García &amp; Hancock &amp; Rotheray" authorityYear="2012" box="[1124,1283,1447,1468]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Quichuana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longicauda" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="CBDAFA651073FFD4AF237CB39F691BAE" box="[1124,1283,1447,1468]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="99">Q. longicauda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="D0E9471E1073FFD4AE4D7CB39F351BAE" box="[1290,1375,1447,1468]" pageId="27" pageNumber="99" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
the basoflagellomere is shorter and wider (
<figureCitation id="61953AF21073FFD4AE467CD29F281BCE" box="[1281,1346,1478,1500]" captionStart="Figures 1–2" captionStartId="2.[164,254,1736,1755]" captionTargetBox="[174,772,1463,1706]" captionTargetId="figure-546@2.[168,776,1461,1707]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figures 1–2. Quichuana right antennae, lateral inner view: 1, Quichuana amazonica sp. nov., male holotype; 2, Quichuana longicauda sp. nov., female paratype; l, distance from top of basoflagellomere and most prominent point of pedicel; w, width of basoflagellomere at the level of the arista base. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5408535" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5408535/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="99">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) than that in the similar 
<taxonomicName id="3EAE5DF41073FFD4AF557CF19EEC1BEB" authorityName=", Knab" authorityYear="1913" box="[1042,1158,1508,1530]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Quichuana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="99" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="picadoi">
<emphasis id="CBDAFA651073FFD4AF557CF19EEC1BEB" box="[1042,1158,1508,1530]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="99">Q. picadoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="61953AF21073FFD4AFDD7CF09F731BE8" box="[1178,1305,1508,1530]" captionStart="Figures 73–79" captionStartId="56.[164,254,1284,1303]" captionTargetBox="[323,1277,195,1250]" captionTargetId="figure-219@56.[323,1283,195,1254]" captionTargetPageId="56" captionText="Figures 73–79. Features of the ‘slender’ and ‘robust’ species of Quichuana. 73–76, ‘slender’ species. 73, Quichuana angustiventris, male from Trinidad with attached puparium, overall appearance, dorsal view; scale bar = 2 mm. 74, Quichuana calathea, male from Costa Rica, eye contiguity and vertical triangle; scale bar = 0.5 mm. 75–76, Quichuana picadoi, male: 75, anterior view; 76, lateral view; scale bar = 1 mm. 77–79, ‘robust’ species. 77, Quichuana fasciata, female lectotype, overall appearance, dorsal view; scale bar = 2 mm. 78, Quichuana dissimilis sp. nov., male holotype, eye contiguity and vertical triangle; scale bar = 1 mm. 79, Quichuana atra sp. nov., female, anterior view; scale bar = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5408583" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5408583/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="99">Fig. 75, 76</figureCitation>
), and the wing is more extensively bare of microtrichia than in the latter species.
</paragraph>
